        <sect1>
            <title>Grappling and Wrestling</title>

            <sect2>
                <title>Attack Opportunities</title>


                <sect3>
                    <title>Grapple (Good)</title>

                    <para>
                        A <e>grapple</e> represents an attempt to hold onto
                        a person and stop them from acting. On a <e>good</e>
                        brawl attack, the attacker can opt to try and
                        grapple their opponent. It is assumed at this point
                        that the attacker has managed to grab hold of some
                        part of the defender - what happens next depends on
                        what the defender does.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If the defender wishes to break free, then both
                        make a second opposed brawl check. The attacker
                        uses strength, the defender may use strength or
                        agility. If the defender succeeds, then the grapple
                        is broken. If the attacker succeeds, then they have
                        kept hold of the defender, and all future actions
                        of the defender will be at -1 to their attribute
                        for each level of success of the attacker. If this
                        brings their agility or strength to less than one,
                        then they are pinned and cannot act.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If the defender wishes, they may perform a counter
                        grapple, in which case both people make a strength
                        based check against a target of 10, with the
                        result being that both opponents are grappled and
                        at penalty to actions.
                    </para>
                </sect3>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Trip (Good)</title>

                    <para>
                        If the attacker gets a <e>good</e> attack, then he
                        may try to trip his opponent, knocking them to the
                        floor. In reality, a trip can be an actual trip, a
                        throw or a push. Both combatents make opposed
                        <y:skeq>
                            <y:attr>strength</y:attr>
                            <y:sk>brawl</y:sk>
                            <die/>
                        </y:skeq>
                        checks, with the attacker gaining a +1 bonus to
                        strength for each extra level of success in the
                        initial attack.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        If the attacker fails, then nothing happens. On
                        success, the defender is thrown to the ground
                        making them prone. Optionally, they may also
                        cause <e>stun</e> damage as normal. Each level
                        of success gives a bonus of +3 to damage.
                    </para>

                    <para>
                        Instead of causing extra damage, the attacker can
                        choose to make the defender land somewhere specific.
                        Somewhere nearby and relatively simple requires a
                        <e>good</e> success (e.g., off an edge, onto a
                        table), whereas a more complex target requires an
                        <e>excellent</e> success (over a wall, through a
                        window).
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Defence Opportunities</title>

                <para>
                    Similar to attacks, a defender making a brawl defence
                    may get the opportunity to make a special move. If at
                    least a <e>good</e> defence is made, then the defender
                    can opt to perform a special action. Performing such
                    an action negates any other benefits of a good defence,
                    such as free strikes (though the attack is prevented).
                </para>

                <sect3>
                    <title>Defensive trip (Good)</title>

                    <para>
                        Turns an attack into a Judo throw.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>

        <sect1 id="fightingdirty">
            <title>Fighting Dirty</title>

            <para>
                Often, the winner of a combat will be whoever has the
                best skill. Sometimes, the winner is the person who is
                willing to cheat. Of course, if the other guy is trying
                to kill you, kicking him in the balls and stabbing him
                in the eye may be the best way to stay alive.
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>Tricks</title>

                <para>
                    When making an attack, you may declare that you want
                    to try a trick. A trick is any non-standard attack,
                    such as throwing dirt in someone's eyes.
                </para>
            </sect2>
        </sect1>
